body:
Title: Amazing Spider-Man #13

Summary: I’ve not been overly enjoying the recent run of Spider-Man, this story had not been an exception, however this issue was a lot stronger than some of the previous ones and felt more like a true Spider-Man comic. I’m looking forward to the upcoming “Hunted” story arc and hopefully the gradual improvement of the recent issues is a positive sign of things to come.

Rating: 7.5/10

summary: Spider-Man (reboot) #1 (2016) JULIE: Miles Morales, go to hell. You beg me for a week to go out with you --- beg me --- and then...
caption:
Spider-Man (reboot) #1 (2016)

JULIE: Miles Morales, go to hell. You beg me for a week to go out with you — beg me — and then you make me wait for an hour.
MILES: Julie. The traffic—
JULIE: Traffic?! You’re not even supposed to leave school grounds.
MILES: I was really looking forward to — Let me —
JULIE: Stop. I’m serious. Weirdo.

The first issue of Bendis’ last run pretty much covers the beginning and end of Miles Morales’ relationship with Black women in the comics.

summary: Hey Kids Comics #2 (September 2018) While it may not be a superhero book, Howard Chaykin’s recent series was about the people...
caption:
Hey Kids Comics #2 (September 2018)

While it may not be a superhero book, Howard Chaykin’s recent series was about the people who got screwed over (and some who did the screwing) in the making of superheroes in the first place.

This cover plays with the notion of the money and credit Steve Ditko didn’t get for co-creating Spider-Man given the character’s transmedial success.
